 in Britain. In the US, it is found mainly in NC, TX, and IN."]},{"name":"Cornfield","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Cranfield  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of Jewish or German   Kornfeld  ."]}]},{"name":"Whitewell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Weitzel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Weitzel","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Weitzel</i>, a pet form of <i>Wizo</i>, a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound names beginning with <i>wīg</i> ‘battle’ or <i>wid(u)</i> ‘wood, forest’.","South German: from a pet form of   Weitz  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Cratfield Whitewell was born in 1356, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Whitewell. She had at least 2 sons with William John Barret. She died in 1424, in London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1356–1424":"1356–1424","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1356–1416":"1356–1416","–1431":"–1431","1400–1467":"1400–1467","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1424":"1424","1336":"1336","1467":"1467","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1431":"1431","about 1400":"umbes 1400","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Halesworth Manor, Suffolkshire, England":"Halesworth, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Halesworth, Suffolk, England":"Halesworth, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1356–1424":"1356–1424","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1356–1416":"1356–1416","–1431":"–1431","1400–1467":"1400–1467","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1424":"1424","1336":"1336","1467":"1467","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1431":"1431","about 1400":"noin 1400","Abt 1400":"noin 1400","1380":"1380","1416":"1416","Halesworth Manor, Suffolkshire, England":"Halesworth, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Halesworth, Suffolk, England":"Halesworth, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1356–1424":"1356–1424","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1356–1416":"1356–1416","–1431":"–1431","1400–1467":"1400–1467","1336–Male":"1336–Décédé","1424":"1424","1336":"1336","1467":"1467","1356":"1356","1400":"1400","1431":"1431","about 1400":"environ 1400","Abt 1400":"environ 1400","1380":"